<paragraph blockId="2.[136,1452,1252,1674]" pageId="2" pageNumber="237">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[189,576,1396,1422]" pageId="2" pageNumber="237">Micromorphological properties:</emphasis>
—SEM observations of the achenes, pollen grains and leaf lower surface of 
<taxonomicName box="[136,398,1432,1458]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Tragopogon" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="2" pageNumber="237" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="anatolicus">
<emphasis box="[136,398,1432,1458]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="237">Tragopogon anatolicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[454,661,1432,1458]" class="Aves" family="Phasianidae" genus="Tragopon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Galliformes" pageId="2" pageNumber="237" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="buphthalmoides">
<emphasis box="[454,661,1432,1458]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="237">T. buphthalmoides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are given in 
<figureCitation box="[811,919,1432,1458]" captionStart-0="FIGURE 4" captionStart-1="FIGURE 5" captionStart-2="FIGURE 6" captionStartId-0="4.[136,229,1182,1204]" captionStartId-1="4.[136,229,2021,2043]" captionStartId-2="5.[136,229,702,724]" captionTargetBox-0="[154,1432,193,1155]" captionTargetBox-1="[309,1278,1266,1994]" captionTargetBox-2="[154,1433,193,670]" captionTargetId-0="figure-27@4.[151,1435,190,1158]" captionTargetId-1="figure-56@4.[306,1281,1266,1997]" captionTargetId-2="figure-18@5.[151,1436,190,677]" captionTargetPageId-0="4" captionTargetPageId-1="4" captionTargetPageId-2="5" captionText-0="FIGURE 4. Scanning electron microscope images of achenes. Tragopogon anatolicus: A–D (50×), E–H (1000×); Tragopogon buphthalmoides: I–L (50×), M–P (1000×)." captionText-1="FIGURE 5. Scanning electron microscope images of pollen grains. Tragopogon anatolicus: A. Polar view. C. Surface ornamentation. Tragopogon buphthalmoides: B. Polar view. D. Surface ornamentation." captionText-2="FIGURE 6. Characters of lower leaf surface under scanning electron microscope. A. Tragopogon anatolicus. B. Tragopogon buphthalmoides." figureDoi-0="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5138800" figureDoi-1="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5138802" figureDoi-2="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5138804" httpUri-0="https://zenodo.org/record/5138800/files/figure.png" httpUri-1="https://zenodo.org/record/5138802/files/figure.png" httpUri-2="https://zenodo.org/record/5138804/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="237">Figs. 4–6</figureCitation>
. As seen in 
<figureCitation box="[1056,1124,1432,1458]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="4.[136,229,1182,1204]" captionTargetBox="[154,1432,193,1155]" captionTargetId="figure-27@4.[151,1435,190,1158]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 4. Scanning electron microscope images of achenes. Tragopogon anatolicus: A–D (50×), E–H (1000×); Tragopogon buphthalmoides: I–L (50×), M–P (1000×)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5138800" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5138800/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="237">Fig. 4</figureCitation>
, the periferal surface of both the annulus and beak are covered with micro-projections in 
<taxonomicName box="[806,1013,1468,1494]" class="Aves" family="Phasianidae" genus="Tragopon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Galliformes" pageId="2" pageNumber="237" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="buphthalmoides">
<emphasis box="[806,1013,1468,1494]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="237">T. buphthalmoides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[1028,1138,1468,1494]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="4.[136,229,1182,1204]" captionTargetBox="[154,1432,193,1155]" captionTargetId="figure-27@4.[151,1435,190,1158]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 4. Scanning electron microscope images of achenes. Tragopogon anatolicus: A–D (50×), E–H (1000×); Tragopogon buphthalmoides: I–L (50×), M–P (1000×)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5138800" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5138800/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="237">
Fig. 
<quantity box="[1080,1119,1468,1494]" metricMagnitude="0" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.0" pageId="2" pageNumber="237" unit="m" value="4.0">4m</quantity>
,n
</figureCitation>
) but they are nearly smooth in 
<taxonomicName box="[166,312,1504,1530]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Tragopogon" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="2" pageNumber="237" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="anatolicus">
<emphasis box="[166,312,1504,1530]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="237">T. anatolicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[329,428,1504,1531]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="4.[136,229,1182,1204]" captionTargetBox="[154,1432,193,1155]" captionTargetId="figure-27@4.[151,1435,190,1158]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 4. Scanning electron microscope images of achenes. Tragopogon anatolicus: A–D (50×), E–H (1000×); Tragopogon buphthalmoides: I–L (50×), M–P (1000×)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5138800" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5138800/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="237">Fig. 4e,f</figureCitation>
). On the other hand, the body of the achenes in both taxa consists of tetragonal or elliptic epidermal cells with smooth and convex periferal surface.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="2.[136,1452,1252,1674]" pageId="2" pageNumber="237">
Pollen grains of 
<taxonomicName box="[371,514,1576,1602]" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Tragopogon" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="2" pageNumber="237" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="species" species="anatolicus">
<emphasis box="[371,514,1576,1602]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="237">T. anatolicus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, studied from the 
<typeStatus box="[715,816,1576,1602]" pageId="2" pageNumber="237">holotype</typeStatus>
, are prolate-spheroidal, tricolporate (
<figureCitation box="[1226,1307,1576,1603]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="4.[136,229,2021,2043]" captionTargetBox="[309,1278,1266,1994]" captionTargetId="figure-56@4.[306,1281,1266,1997]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 5. Scanning electron microscope images of pollen grains. Tragopogon anatolicus: A. Polar view. C. Surface ornamentation. Tragopogon buphthalmoides: B. Polar view. D. Surface ornamentation." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5138802" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5138802/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="237">Fig. 5a</figureCitation>
); it is oblatespheroidal, tricolporate in 
<taxonomicName box="[432,638,1612,1638]" class="Aves" family="Phasianidae" genus="Tragopon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Galliformes" pageId="2" pageNumber="237" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="buphthalmoides">
<emphasis box="[432,638,1612,1638]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="237">T. buphthalmoides</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[654,738,1612,1639]" captionStart="FIGURE 5" captionStartId="4.[136,229,2021,2043]" captionTargetBox="[309,1278,1266,1994]" captionTargetId="figure-56@4.[306,1281,1266,1997]" captionTargetPageId="4" captionText="FIGURE 5. Scanning electron microscope images of pollen grains. Tragopogon anatolicus: A. Polar view. C. Surface ornamentation. Tragopogon buphthalmoides: B. Polar view. D. Surface ornamentation." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5138802" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5138802/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="237">Fig. 5b</figureCitation>
). This type of pollen grain is common in the genus 
<taxonomicName authority="(Blackmore 1982)" baseAuthorityName="Blackmore" baseAuthorityYear="1982" class="Magnoliopsida" family="Asteraceae" genus="Tragopogon" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asterales" pageId="2" pageNumber="237" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1314,1451,1613,1638]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="237">Tragopogon</emphasis>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Blackmore, S." box="[143,335,1648,1674]" pageId="2" pageNumber="237" pagination="149 - 160" refId="ref3399" refString="Blackmore, S. (1982) Palynology of subtribe Scorzonerinae (Compositae: Lactuceae) and its taxonomic significance. Grana 21 (3): 149 - 160. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1080 / 00173138209427691" type="journal article" year="1982">Blackmore 1982</bibRefCitation>
)
</taxonomicName>
. Other palynological features determined in the present study are given in 
<tableCitation box="[1177,1261,1648,1674]" captionStart="TABLE 1" captionStartId="2.[136,224,1715,1739]" captionText="TABLE 1. Palynological properties of Tragopogon anatolicus and related species." pageId="2" pageNumber="237">Table 1</tableCitation>
.
</paragraph>
